III. Matth. 20. 26. but it ſhall not be ſo among you. Heathen princes uſe their power in order to their own profit, and pleaſure, and praiſe (
                              〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                           ) behaving themſelves as Lords and Maſters over ſo many Servants. Your pre-eminence brings along with it no great ſecular felicity, but an office of burden, and pains and humility, and doing of ſervice. The pre-eminence of Chriſt himſelf was ſuch. This excludes not diſciples of Chriſt from power: for he ownes the title of Lord and maſter, Joh. 13. 13. but from Lording, and governing by violence, and in an imperious way, ſeeking their own gain and honour.

II. Phil. 4. 11. I have learned in what ſtate ſoever I am, &c. This is the knowledge which makes us Wiſe, Rich, Free, Happy, every thing; ſupplies all our wants, and ſets us above danger; to have learnt quietly to ſubmit our ſelves to God in all the variety of diſpenſations, to be content (
                              〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                           ) to be ſelfſufficient, to have proviſion within our ſelvs againſt all accidents.
